<subSubSection lastPageId="71" lastPageNumber="72" pageId="70" pageNumber="71" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="70.[151,1436,1907,2042]" lastBlockId="71.[151,1437,151,393]" lastPageId="71" lastPageNumber="72" pageId="70" pageNumber="71">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,308,1979,2005]" pageId="70" pageNumber="71">Remarks</emphasis>
. In his description of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Chevreux" authorityYear="1895" box="[557,693,1979,2005]" class="Malacostraca" family="Synopiidae" genus="Pseudotiron" kingdom="Animalia" order="Amphipoda" pageId="70" pageNumber="71" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[557,693,1979,2005]" italics="true" pageId="70" pageNumber="71">Pseudotiron</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(?) 
<taxonomicName authority="J. L. Barnard (1967)" authorityName="J. L. Barnard" authorityYear="1967" box="[740,1021,1979,2006]" class="Malacostraca" family="Synopiidae" genus="Pseudotiron" kingdom="Animalia" order="Amphipoda" pageId="70" pageNumber="71" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="coas">
<emphasis box="[740,791,1980,2005]" italics="true" pageId="70" pageNumber="71">coas</emphasis>
J.L. 
<bibRefCitation author="Barnard, J. L." box="[849,1021,1979,2006]" pageId="70" pageNumber="71" pagination="1 - 205" refId="ref48389" refString="Barnard, J. L. (1967) Bathyal and Abyssal Gammaridean Amphipoda of Cedros Trench, Baja California. United States National Museum Bulletin, 260, 1 - 205. https: // doi. org / 10.5479 / si. 03629236.260.1" type="journal article" year="1967">Barnard (1967)</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
expressed some doubt as to whether the species belonged in that genus. He did not repeat or comment on his doubt in a subsequent brief diagnosis of the species (J.L. 
<bibRefCitation author="Barnard, J. L." box="[341,506,151,177]" pageId="71" pageNumber="72" pagination="1 - 94" refId="ref48434" refString="Barnard, J. L. (1972) A Review of the Family Synopiidae (= Tironidae), Mainly Distributed in the Deep Sea (Crustacea: Amphipoda). Smithsonian Contributions to Zoology, 124 (1 - 4), 1 - 94. https: // doi. org / 10.5479 / si. 00810282.124" type="journal article" year="1972">Barnard, 1972</bibRefCitation>
). 
<taxonomicName authorityName="J. L. Barnard" authorityYear="1967" box="[527,721,151,177]" class="Malacostraca" family="Synopiidae" genus="Pseudotiron" kingdom="Animalia" order="Amphipoda" pageId="71" pageNumber="72" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="coas">
<emphasis box="[527,721,151,177]" italics="true" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">Pseudotiron coas</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
shares with 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Chevreux" authorityYear="1895" box="[865,987,151,177]" class="Malacostraca" family="Synopiidae" genus="Pseudotiron" kingdom="Animalia" order="Amphipoda" pageId="71" pageNumber="72" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bouvieri">
<emphasis box="[865,987,151,177]" italics="true" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">P. bouvieri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
the distinctive head-shape with a short, rounded rostrum and a straight, vertical lateral margin joining the lower margin in a rounded, nearly right angle; gnathopods are simple, elongate; pereopods 3–7 are typically pre-stubby; the telson is elongate and fully cleft; uropod 3 rami of subequal length, with some apical robust setae apparently broken off (sockets visible on both rami). The main difference between 
<taxonomicName authorityName="J. L. Barnard" authorityYear="1967" box="[483,677,295,321]" class="Malacostraca" family="Synopiidae" genus="Pseudotiron" kingdom="Animalia" order="Amphipoda" pageId="71" pageNumber="72" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="coas">
<emphasis box="[483,677,295,321]" italics="true" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">Pseudotiron coas</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Chevreux" authorityYear="1895" box="[731,851,295,321]" class="Malacostraca" family="Synopiidae" genus="Pseudotiron" kingdom="Animalia" order="Amphipoda" pageId="71" pageNumber="72" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bouvieri">
<emphasis box="[731,851,295,321]" italics="true" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">P. bouvieri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is the shape of coxal plate 3, which is shown by J.L. 
<bibRefCitation author="Barnard, J. L." box="[151,316,331,357]" pageId="71" pageNumber="72" pagination="1 - 205" refId="ref48389" refString="Barnard, J. L. (1967) Bathyal and Abyssal Gammaridean Amphipoda of Cedros Trench, Baja California. United States National Museum Bulletin, 260, 1 - 205. https: // doi. org / 10.5479 / si. 03629236.260.1" type="journal article" year="1967">Barnard (1967</bibRefCitation>
, fig. 81k) to be nearly rectangular with concave posterior margin, as opposed to the pelagont, angular posterior projection of the latter species.
</paragraph>
